DATA DESCRIPTION¶

Features:

  1. months_as_customer: It denotes the number of months for which the customer is associated with the insurance company.
  2. age: continuous. It denotes the age of the person.
  3. policy_number: The policy number.
  4. policy_bind_date: Start date of the policy.
  5. policy_state: The state where the policy is registered.
  6. policy_csl-combined single limits. How much of the bodily injury will be covered from the total damage. https://www.berkshireinsuranceservices.com/arecombinedsinglelimitsbetter
  7. policy_deductable: The amount paid out of pocket by the policy-holder before an insurance provider will pay any expenses.
  8. policy_annual_premium: The yearly premium for the policy.
  9. umbrella_limit: An umbrella insurance policy is extra liability insurance coverage that goes beyond the limits of the insured's homeowners, auto or watercraft insurance. It provides an additional layer of security to those who are at risk of being sued for damages to other people's property or injuries caused to others in an accident.
  10. insured_zip: The zip code where the policy is registered.
  11. insured_sex: It denotes the person's gender.
  12. insured_education_level: The highest educational qualification of the policy-holder.
  13. insured_occupation: The occupation of the policy-holder.
  14. insured_hobbies: The hobbies of the policy-holder.
  15. insured_relationship: Dependents on the policy-holder.
  16. capital-gain: It denotes the monitory gains by the person.
  17. capital-loss: It denotes the monitory loss by the person.
  18. incident_date: The date when the incident happened.
  19. incident_type: The type of the incident.
  20. collision_type: The type of collision that took place.
  21. incident_severity: The severity of the incident.
  22. authorities_contacted: Which authority was contacted.
  23. incident_state: The state in which the incident took place.
  24. incident_city: The city in which the incident took place.
  25. incident_location: The street in which the incident took place.
  26. incident_hour_of_the_day: The time of the day when the incident took place.
  27. property_damage: If any property damage was done.
  28. bodily_injuries: Number of bodily injuries.
  29. Witnesses: Number of witnesses present.
  30. police_report_available: Is the police report available.
  31. total_claim_amount: Total amount claimed by the customer.
  32. injury_claim: Amount claimed for injury
  33. property_claim: Amount claimed for property damage.
  34. vehicle_claim: Amount claimed for vehicle damage.
  35. auto_make: The manufacturer of the vehicle
  36. auto_model: The model of the vehicle.
  37. auto_year: The year of manufacture of the vehicle.

Target Label: Whether the claim is fraudulent or not.

  1. fraud_reported: Y or N

# we can observe that-

# Following features should be of type datetime , but are identified as object or numeric
# policy_bind_date , incident_date , auto_year

# We convert them to datetime cuz , We want to create new features from them , instead of dropping them off------Features will be created later on
# claim_duration = policy_bind_date -incident_date ---- then remove the two columns from data , but keep them during html form input
# car_duration = auto_year - incident_date  --- then remove the two columns from data , but keep them during html form input

data.auto_year=pd.to_datetime(data.auto_year,format="%Y")
data.policy_bind_date=pd.to_datetime(data.policy_bind_date)
data.incident_date=pd.to_datetime(data.incident_date)

# Remove following columns-
# _c39 -- contains all nan values , so drop them
# insured_zip, policy_number , incident_location ---- Since all the values are unique and can be unique for every person , 
#                                                    they don't provide any information ; so, we'll drop these features

data=data.drop(['insured_zip', 'policy_number' , 'incident_location', '_c39'],axis=1)

# Mean Encoding --- policy_state, policy_csl ,insured_hobbies, insured_relationship ,collision_type,incident_state,incident_city,auto_make , auto_model
# Target guided ordinal Encoding --- insured_occupation , incident_severity , authorities_contacted
# One hot --- insured_sex , property damage,police_report_available , fraud reported
# Freq enc -- incident type
# Ordinal enc --- education level
In [34]:
# Explation for choosing the respective Encoding Methods

# We did fequency encoding for incident type because its frequency seemed to have a direct relation with the count of fraudulent autcomes
# Mean Encoding for the given columns cuz , those columns didn't have any ordinal order - so no ordinal enc ; have many unique categories - so one hot encoding would lead to 
#                                           curse of dimensionality ; their frequency didn't have any relation with the count of fraud outcomes
# One Hot Encoding - for all columns having only two categories
# Target Guided Ordinal Encoding - These features have some ordinal order , but we are not sure of it ; so we rank them in order of how well they predict the Target Variable
In [35]:
# One Hot Encoding

sex_map={'MALE':1,'FEMALE':0}
data.insured_sex=data.insured_sex.map(sex_map)

yes_no_map={'YES':1,"NO":0}
data.property_damage=data.property_damage.map(yes_no_map)

data.police_report_available=data.police_report_available.map(yes_no_map)

fraud_map={'Y':1,"N":0}
data.fraud_reported=data.fraud_reported.map(fraud_map)

# Finding Higly Correlated Columns

def correlation(data,threshold):
    col_corr=set()
    cor=data.corr()
    for i in range(len(cor.columns)):
        for j in range(len(cor.columns)):
            if (abs(cor.iloc[i,j]) > threshold) and i!=j:
                if (cor.columns[j] in col_corr) or (cor.columns[i] in col_corr):
                    continue
                print("\n",cor.columns[i],"-----",cor.columns[j])
                print(abs(cor.iloc[i,j]))
                colname=cor.columns[i]
                col_corr.add(colname)
    return col_corr

a=correlation(data.drop(['fraud_reported'],axis=1),0.9)

# FILTER METHOD - CORRELATION

def cor_selector(X, y,num_feats):
    cor_list = []
    feature_name = X.columns.tolist()
    # calculate the correlation with y for each feature
    for i in X.columns.tolist():
        cor = np.corrcoef(X[i], y)[0, 1]
        cor_list.append(cor)
    # replace NaN with 0
    cor_list = [0 if np.isnan(i) else i for i in cor_list]
    # feature name
    cor_feature = X.iloc[:,np.argsort(np.abs(cor_list))[-num_feats:]].columns.tolist()
    # feature selection? 0 for not select, 1 for select
    cor_support = [True if i in cor_feature else False for i in feature_name]
    return cor_support, cor_feature


cor_support, cor_feature = cor_selector(data.drop(['fraud_reported'],axis=1),data.fraud_reported,20)
data.drop(['fraud_reported'],axis=1).columns[cor_support]

# Evaluation metric for models -Recall ( Since , it is important to classify all frauds as frauds , else the company will ncur huge losses )
# From the Company's point of view , it is much reasonable to choose Recall as metric
# From the customers point of view , it is easonable to choose Precision -- since we want to see - how trustable the model in terms of predicting fraud (Out of the predicted frauds , how many are actually frauds)

# we want a sweet spot b/w recall and precision , with more emphasis on improving Recall
In [89]:
#Trying Logistic Regression

import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score,accuracy_score,roc_auc_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score , RepeatedStratifiedKFold

scores_logreg=[]
accuracy_logreg=[]

# Standardizing the data

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler=StandardScaler()

for i in [data,data_c1,data_c2,data_c3,data_c4]:
        X=i.drop(['fraud_reported'],axis=1)
        X=scaler.fit_transform(X)
        y=i.fraud_reported

        logreg=LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000,solver='newton-cg')
        cv=RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=5,random_state=1)

        #collecting recall
        recall=cross_val_score(logreg,X,y,cv=cv,scoring='recall')
        scores_logreg.append(recall.mean())
        
        #collecting accuracy
        acc=cross_val_score(logreg,X,y,cv=cv,scoring='accuracy')
        accuracy_logreg.append(acc.mean())

print(f"Cross Validation Score : \n")    
print(f"Entire Data--Recall:{scores_logreg[0]}  Accuracy :{accuracy_logreg[0]} ") 
print(f"Cluster 1--Recall:{scores_logreg[1]}  Accuracy :{accuracy_logreg[1]} ")
print(f"Cluster 2--Recall:{scores_logreg[2]}  Accuracy :{accuracy_logreg[2]} ")
print(f"Cluster 3--Recall:{scores_logreg[3]}  Accuracy :{accuracy_logreg[3]} ")
print(f"Cluster 4--Recall:{scores_logreg[4]}  Accuracy :{accuracy_logreg[4]} ")

# Since, the company aims to reduce losses due to not being able to identify Fraudulent Claims ; we choose model which gives us highest recall 

# However, in my opinion , for the overall growth of the company , we should choose a model which is considerably good , in both recall and precision . Because , if the precision will be low ,
#  that would imply that non-fraudulent claims are being classified as fraud ---- this would reduce the customer satisfaction
In [270]:
# COMPARING MODELS GIVING BEST RECALL AND ACCURACY FOR THE CLUSTERS AND CHOOSING THE APPROPRIATE MODEL FOR THEM


# We can Observe that Some Models generalize better , after data has been clustered 
# RF,SVC,LogReg and KNN generalize better on the dataset after clustering 

# For Cluster 1 and Cluster 3 -- XGB was giving best results , nut we chose other models which gave simialar results and were
# computationally less expensive in comparision

# for cluster 2 - RF and XGB gave similar result ; but we considered RF cuz it was computationally less expensive
# Cluster 1 - KNN ( acc:79 , recall:95) ; RF (acc:89 , recall:89) --- We choose Random Forest as model for cluster 1 as we want a model that peroforms good overall 
                                                                    # Here , KNN gives a recall , only sightly better than RF ; but it's accuracy is very low compared to RF 
# Cluster 2 - KNN ( acc:81, recall:96) ; ADB( acc:88 , recall:88) --- We choose KNN Classifier as our model
# Cluster 3 - KNN ( acc:75 , recall:98) ; ADB ( acc:91 , recall:96) --- We choose ADB as our model
# Cluster 4 KNN( acc: 79 , recall:100) ; Logistic Reg ( acc:90 , recall: 97) --- We choose Logistic Regression as our Model

y=data_c1.fraud_reported

# rf=RandomForestClassifier()
# rf.fit(X,y)

grid_param={'n_estimators':[50,70,100,120],
            'criterion':["gini","entropy"], 
            'max_depth':[5,10,12,15],
            'min_samples_leaf':[5,10,15,20]
            }

grid_search=GridSearchCV(estimator=RandomForestClassifier(),scoring=['recall','accuracy'] ,cv=5,refit='recall',param_grid=grid_param,n_jobs=-1)

X=scaler.fit_transform(X)
y=data_c4.fraud_reported
X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,np.ravel(y),test_size=0.3,random_state=2)

logreg=LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000,solver='newton-cg')
logreg.fit(X_train,y_train)

y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)
y_proba=logreg.predict_proba(X_test)

print(f"Training Recall : {recall_score(y_train,logreg.predict(X_train))}")
print(f"Testing Recall : {recall_score(y_test,y_pred)}")
print(f"Testing Accuracy : {accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred)}")

plot_confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred)
plot_roc(y_test,y_proba)

# function to find closest cluster center , from test point

def find_cluster(test_point):
    distances=[]
    for center in kmeans.cluster_centers_:
        dist=np.linalg.norm(center-test_point)
        distances.append(dist)
        
    dist_frame=pd.DataFrame(data=distances,columns=['Distances'])
    cluster=dist_frame.Distances.idxmin()
    print(f"The point belongs to cluster {cluster}")
    
    return cluster
